I hope that the foregoing came through okay witout getting shifted back to TO.  My suggestions are listed in the brackets.  I was short of time.  'm sure if I did someone else will point them out.  A few changes may be due to differences in dialect, but frequently, it is the cognitive dissonance caused by the TO in our brains interfering with the ability to hear what we are saying.

Paige Gabhart

paulhtremblay wrote:

Hi group,

I'm new here. I've just uploaded a file called sample_princess. pdf.
The file contains a short fairly tale I found that is artificially
constructed to include all 41 English sounds. (Though, I had to add an
extra sentence at the end to use the "OI" sound.)

I typed this tale in TO (traditional orthography) , ASCII IPA, and of
course, Quickscript itself. I think the file might prove useful for
others first learning, as I am doing. First, though, I need to correct
all mistakes in it, so if anyone has the chance to look at it I'd
appreciate it.
